<subSubSection id="C321652DFFC6C21AF3C23CFEFDD09D4B" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8436A6FFC6C21AF3C23CFEFDD09D4B" blockId="2.[151,1436,1156,1561]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="B94FEAB4FFC6C21AF3C23CFEFEAB9CE0" bold="true" box="[199,345,1226,1250]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Distribution.</emphasis>
New for 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF2BA3CFEFDFA9CE3" box="[447,520,1226,1249]" name="Ghana" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Ghana</collectingCountry>
. The species was so far recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF0AC3CFEFBE99CE3" box="[937,1051,1226,1249]" name="Cameroon" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF7203CFEFA6E9CE3" box="[1061,1436,1226,1249]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Democratic Republic of the Congo</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF3C03CD9FEEB9D06" box="[197,281,1261,1284]" name="Nigeria" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
. The new data indicate that the species also inhabits the narrow, western part of the African rainforest zone reaching the westernmost part of 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF2F83D24FDBC9D25" box="[509,590,1296,1319]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Guinea</collectingCountry>
. The species is therefore likely to be found in other countries located along the northern coast of the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF2CB3D06FDEC9D4B" box="[462,542,1330,1353]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Guinea</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C321652DFFC6C21AF3C23D60FC419E1B" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8436A6FFC6C21AF3C23D60FC419E1B" blockId="2.[151,1436,1156,1561]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="B94FEAB4FFC6C21AF3C23D60FEC79D6E" bold="true" box="[199,309,1364,1388]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D25FFC6C21AF2453D61FE3A9D6E" box="[320,456,1365,1388]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Metarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="postrosea">
<emphasis id="B94FEAB4FFC6C21AF2453D61FE3A9D6E" box="[320,456,1365,1388]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">R. postrosea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be confused with some other members of the genus. Populations from 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7636FFC6C21AF62F3D61FA829D6E" box="[1322,1392,1365,1388]" name="Ghana" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">Ghana</collectingCountry>
are characterized by the much more extensive yellow colouration of the hind wing (
<figureCitation id="13002A23FFC6C21AF7013D4CFBB59D8D" box="[1028,1095,1400,1423]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,1660,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,1615,1925]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. (A) Pseudothyretes kamitugensis. (B) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea. (C) Metarctia paremphares. (D) Metarctia priscilla. (E) Metarctia sp. (scale bar = 10 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206671/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF32481FFC6C21AF73D3D4CFBB59D8D" box="[1080,1095,1400,1423]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Only one female has a well visible pale pinkish-yellow hind wing. The most reliable character distinguishing the species is the shape of male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="13002A23FFC6C21AF2043D89FEB09DD6" box="[257,322,1469,1492]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1295,1319]" captionTargetBox="[186,1350,239,1229]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,194,1271]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. (A – C) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea (gs S 133 (3) S 134 (Ƥ), ISEA): (A) Male genitalia. (B) Phallus. (C) Female genitalia. (D – E) Metarctia paremphares (gs S 136, ISEA): (D) Male genitalia. (E) Phallus. (F – G) Metarctia priscilla (gs S 137, ISEA): (F) Male genitalia. (G) Phallus. (H) Metarctia haematica (gs S 131, ISEA) female genitalia. (I) Metarctia sp. (gs S 139, ISEA) female genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206672/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">
Figs 
<number id="3DF32481FFC6C21AF2333D89FEB09DD6" box="[310,322,1469,1492]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A–B) (gs - S 
<number id="3DF32481FFC6C21AF2CC3D89FE019DD6" box="[457,499,1469,1492]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" value="133.0">133</number>
, 
<collectionCode id="ED2AAE63FFC6C21AF2FA3D89FDCD9DD6" box="[511,575,1469,1492]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">ISEA</collectionCode>
). The specific characters of the female genitalia are not known yet (
<figureCitation id="13002A23FFC6C21AF6093D89FAB89DD6" box="[1292,1354,1469,1492]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1295,1319]" captionTargetBox="[186,1350,239,1229]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,194,1271]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. (A – C) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea (gs S 133 (3) S 134 (Ƥ), ISEA): (A) Male genitalia. (B) Phallus. (C) Female genitalia. (D – E) Metarctia paremphares (gs S 136, ISEA): (D) Male genitalia. (E) Phallus. (F – G) Metarctia priscilla (gs S 137, ISEA): (F) Male genitalia. (G) Phallus. (H) Metarctia haematica (gs S 131, ISEA) female genitalia. (I) Metarctia sp. (gs S 139, ISEA) female genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206672/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF32481FFC6C21AF63B3D89FAB89DD6" box="[1342,1354,1469,1492]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C) (gs - S 
<number id="3DF32481FFC6C21AF3A03DD4FF229DF5" box="[165,208,1504,1527]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56" value="134.0">134</number>
, 
<collectionCode id="ED2AAE63FFC6C21AF3E53DD4FED29DF5" box="[224,288,1504,1527]" pageId="2" pageNumber="56">ISEA</collectionCode>
). Their morphology does not differ from the related species belonging to the nominal subgenus. An additional problem is that the females of several species are still unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
